#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:3
msgid "Building Python Packages from Source"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:5
msgid ""
"This document describes building Python packages following the [PEP 517]"
"(https://peps.python.org/pep-0517/) to Pyodide. In other words, the package "
"should be buildable with `python -m build` command. Otherwise, the package "
"would likely require a complex setup to build it. Please contact the package "
"maintainer to discuss how to build the package with Pyodide build system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:10
msgid ""
"[!NOTE] It is assumed that the person reading this article understands the "
"build system for the package they are trying to build, or at least has built "
"the package in the native environment themselves. If not, please refer to "
"the package's documentation for building instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:15
msgid "Quickstart"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:17
msgid ""
"Go to the directory into the package folder where the `pyproject.toml` or "
"`setup.py` file is located. Then run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:20
msgid "pyodide build\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:24
msgid ""
"in the package folder. This command produces a wheel in the `dist/` folder, "
"similarly to the [PyPA build](https://pypa-build.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) "
"command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:28
msgid ""
"If you need to add custom compiler / linker flags to the compiler "
"invocations, you can set the `CFLAGS`, `CXXFLAGS` and `LDFLAGS` environment "
"variables. For instance, to make a debug build, you can use: `CFLAGS=-g2 "
"LDFLAGS=-g2 pyodide build`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:32
msgid ""
"`pyodide build` invokes a slightly modified version of the `pypa/build` "
"build frontend so the behavior should be similar to what happens if you do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:35
msgid ""
"pip install build\n"
"python -m build\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:40
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:42
msgid ""
"the resulting package wheels have a file name of the form `*-cpXXX-cpXXX-"
"pyodide_XXXX_X_wasm_32.whl` and are compatible only for a given Pyodide "
"versions. In the Pyodide distribution, Python and Emscripten are updated "
"simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:46
msgid ""
"for now, PyPI does not support emscripten/wasm32 wheels so you will not be "
"able to upload them there. (See [PEP 783](https://peps.python.org/pep-0783/) "
"for future plans.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:49
msgid "Debugging build issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:51
msgid ""
"If you run into problems with `pyodide build`, first make sure that building "
"a native wheel with `pypa/build` works. If it does, compare the output of "
"`pyodide build` with the output of `python -m build`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:55
msgid ""
"Once you've found the differences and errors, analyze them to see if they "
"apply to any of the cases below. If none of them apply or are difficult to "
"resolve, please open an issue in Pyodide repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:58
msgid "Failed locating libraries / Missing libraries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:60
msgid ""
"If you see errors like `error: cannot find -l<libname>` or `error: <libname> "
"not found`, it means that the build system cannot locate the library, or the "
"library is not properly built against WebAssembly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:63
msgid ""
"If you are relying on CMake's `find_package` or Meson's `find_library` to "
"locate the library, it might not be able to find the library, because the "
"cross-compiled libraries are not in the default search path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:66
msgid ""
"In that case, you need to explicitly specify the library paths in some way. "
"If you are the package maintainer, please update your build system to locate "
"the libraries in the cross-compiled library path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:69
msgid "Linker error: function signature mismatch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:71
msgid "If you see errors like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:73
msgid ""
"wasm-ld: error: function signature mismatch: some_func\n"
">>> defined as (i32, i32) -> i32 in some_static_lib.a(a.o)\n"
">>> defined as (i32) -> i32 in b.o\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:79
msgid ""
"it means that there is a function signature mismatch in your C/C++ code. "
"WASM is very strict about function signatures, and the linker will fail if "
"it finds a mismatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:82
msgid ""
"Check {ref}`function-signature-mismatch` for more details on how to debug "
"this issue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:84
msgid "Testing packages against Pyodide"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:86
msgid ""
"Pyodide provides an experimental command line runner for testing packages "
"against Pyodide. Using it requires nodejs version 20 or newer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:89
msgid "The way it works is simple: you can create a virtual environment with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:91
msgid "pyodide venv .venv-pyodide\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:95
msgid "Activate it just like a normal virtual environment:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:97
msgid "source .venv-pyodide/bin/activate\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:101
msgid ""
"As a warning, things are pretty weird inside of the Pyodide virtual "
"environment because `python` points to the Pyodide Python runtime. Any "
"program that uses Python and is sensitive to the current virtual environment "
"will probably break."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:105
msgid ""
"You can install whatever dependencies you need with pip. For a pure Python "
"package, the following will work:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:108
msgid "pip install -e .\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:112
msgid ""
"For a binary package, you will need to build a wheel with `pyodide build` "
"and then point `pip` directly to the built wheel. For now, editable installs "
"won't work with binary packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:116
msgid ""
"# Build the binary package\n"
"pyodide build\n"
"# Install it\n"
"pip install dist/the_wheel-cp312-cp312-pyodide_2024_0_wasm32.whl[tests]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:123
msgid ""
"To test, you can generally run the same script as you would usually do. For "
"many packages this will be:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:126
msgid "python -m pytest\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:130
msgid ""
"but for instance `numpy` uses a file called `runtests.py`; the following "
"works:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:132
msgid "python runtests.py\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:136
msgid ""
"and you can pass options to it just like normal. Currently `subprocess` "
"doesn't work, so if you have a test runner that uses `subprocess` then it "
"cannot be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:140
msgid "Github Actions build examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:142
msgid ""
"This is a complete example for building a Pyodide wheel out of tree using "
"`pyodide build` directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:145
msgid ""
"runs-on: ubuntu-22.04 # or ubuntu-latest\n"
"  steps:\n"
"  - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n"
"  - uses: actions/setup-python@v5\n"
"    with:\n"
"       python-version: 3.13\n"
"  - run: |\n"
"      pip install pyodide-build>=0.29.2\n"
"      echo EMSCRIPTEN_VERSION=$(pyodide config get emscripten_version) >> "
"$GITHUB_ENV\n"
"  - uses: mymindstorm/setup-emsdk@v14\n"
"    with:\n"
"       version: ${{ env.EMSCRIPTEN_VERSION }}\n"
"  - run: pyodide build\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:161
msgid ""
"And this is an example using `cibuildwheel` to build a Pyodide wheel out of "
"tree:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:163
msgid ""
"runs-on: ubuntu-22.04 # or ubuntu-latest\n"
"  steps:\n"
"  - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n"
"  - uses: pypa/cibuildwheel@v2.20.0\n"
"    env:\n"
"       CIBW_PLATFORM: pyodide\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-from-source.md:172
msgid ""
"For an example \"in the wild\" of a GitHub Action to build and test a wheel "
"against Pyodide, see [the numpy CI](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/blob/"
"main/.github/workflows/emscripten.yml)"
msgstr ""
